"{\"continue\":{\"rvcontinue\":\"20161229021121|757148470\",\"continue\":\"||\"},\"warnings\":{\"main\":{\"*\":\"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application.\"},\"revisions\":{\"*\":\"Because \\\"rvslots\\\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used.\"}},\"query\":{\"normalized\":[{\"from\":\"Charlie_Crist\",\"to\":\"Charlie Crist\"}],\"pages\":{\"1224681\":{\"pageid\":1224681,\"ns\":0,\"title\":\"Charlie Crist\",\"revisions\":[{\"timestamp\":\"2016-12-30T05:08:08Z\",\"contentformat\":\"text/x-wiki\",\"contentmodel\":\"wikitext\",\"*\":\"{{Infobox officeholder\\n|name         = Charlie Crist\\n|image        = Gov charlie crist.jpg\\n|state        = [[Florida]]\\n|district     = {{ushr|FL|13|13th}}\\n|term_start   = January 3, 2017\\n|term_end     = \\n|succeeding   = [[David Jolly]]\\n|predecessor  = David Jolly\\n|successor    = \\n|order1       = [[List of Governors of Florida|44th]] [[Governor of Florida]]\\n|lieutenant1  = [[Jeff Kottkamp]]\\n|term_start1  = January 2, 2007\\n|term_end1    = January 4, 2011\\n|predecessor1 = [[Jeb Bush]]\\n|successor1   = [[Rick Scott]]\\n|office2      = 35th [[Florida Attorney General|Attorney General of Florida]]\\n|governor2    = Jeb Bush\\n|term_start2  = January 7, 2003\\n|term_end2    = January 2, 2007\\n|predecessor2 = [[Richard E. Doran|Richard Doran]]\\n|successor2   = [[Bill McCollum]]\\n|office3      = 21st [[Florida Department of Education|Education Commissioner of Florida]]\\n|governor3    = Jeb Bush\\n|term_start3  = January 3, 2001\\n|term_end3    = January 7, 2003\\n|predecessor3 = [[Tom Gallagher]]\\n|successor3   = Jim Horne\\n|office4      = Member of the [[Florida Senate]]<br />from the 20th District\\n|term_start4  = November 3, 1992\\n|term_end4    = November 3, 1998\\n|predecessor4 = Redistricted\\n|successor4   = [[Jim Sebesta]]\\n|birth_name   = Charles Joseph Crist, Jr.\\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1956|7|24}}\\n|birth_place  = [[Altoona, Pennsylvania]], [[United States|U.S.]]\\n|death_date   = \\n|death_place  = \\n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] {{small|(1974\\u20132010)}}<br>[[Independent politician|Independent]] {{small|(2010\\u20132012)}}<br>[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] {{small|(2012\\u2013present)}}\\n|spouse       = Amanda Morrow {{small|(1979\\u20131980)}}<br>[[Carole Crist]] {{small|(m. 2008)}}\\n|alma_mater   = [[Wake Forest University]]<br>[[Florida State University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[Samford University]] {{small|([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\\n|website      = {{url|charliecrist.com|Personal website}}\\n|signature    = Charlie Crist Signature.svg\\n}}\\n'''Charles Joseph''' \\\"'''Charlie'''\\\" '''Crist, Jr.''' ({{IPAc-en|\\u02c8|k|r|\\u026a|s|t}}; born July 24, 1956) is an American attorney and politician who served as the [[List of Governors of Florida|44th Governor of Florida]] from 2007 to 2011. He is also the Congressman-elect from {{ushr|Florida|13}} and will take office in January 2017.\\n\\nCrist began his political career as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], serving in the [[Florida Senate]] from 1993 to 1999, running unsuccessfully for the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] in [[United States Senate election in Florida, 1998|1998]] when he challenged incumbent [[Bob Graham]] and then serving as [[Florida Department of Education|Florida Education Commissioner]] from 2001 to 2003 and [[Florida Attorney General]] from 2003 to 2007, before being elected Governor in [[Florida gubernatorial election, 2006|2006]].\\n\\nCrist decided not to run for re-election as Governor in [[Florida gubernatorial election, 2010|2010]], instead announcing on May 12, 2009 that he was running for the U.S. Senate seat being vacated by Republican Senator [[Mel Martinez]]. After initially leading in the race for the Republican nomination, he was overtaken in the polls by [[Marco Rubio]], and in April 2010, Crist left the Republican Party and ran as an [[Independent (politician)|Independent]].<ref name=\\\"online.wsj.com\\\">{{cite news |title=Crist Looks to Go It Alone |work=The Wall Street Journal |last=Wallsten |first=Peter; Bauerlein, Valerie |date=April 29, 2010 |url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052748704423504575212320310724084 }}</ref> In the general election, he lost to Rubio in a three-way race, taking 30% of the vote to Rubio's 49% and Democratic nominee [[Kendrick Meek]]'s 20%. Crist's term as Governor ended in January 2011.\\n\\nOn December 7, 2012, he joined the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], having endorsed President [[Barack Obama]] for re-election in [[United States presidential election, 2012|2012]].<ref name=\\\"changing\\\">{{cite news | url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/09/us/politics/charlie-crist-former-florida-governor-joins-democratic-party.html | title=Changing Affiliation Again, Former Governor of Florida Becomes a Democrat | agency=Associated Press | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=December 8, 2012 | accessdate=March 26, 2013}}</ref> On November 1, 2013, he announced that he was running for governor in the [[Florida gubernatorial election, 2014|2014 election]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Associated Press|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/11/charlie-crist-democrat-florida-governor-race-99244.html|title=Ex-GOP Fla. Gov. Charlie Crist to run for job as Democrat|publisher=Politico|date=November 1, 2013 |accessdate=November 1, 2013}}</ref> However, he was defeated by incumbent Governor [[Rick Scott]], losing by a 1% margin.<ref>http://enight.elections.myflorida.com/StateOffices/</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Adam C. Smith |author2=Steve Bousquet |author3=Katie Sanders |url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/politics/stateroundup/gov-rick-scott-leads-charlie-crist-in-early-returns/2205127|title=Florida Gov. Rick Scott defeats Charlie Crist for re-election|publisher=Tampa Bay Times|date=November 4, 2014|accessdate=November 6, 2014}}</ref> In [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2016|2016]] Crist was elected to the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[Florida's 13th congressional district]], defeating incumbent David Jolly by a margin of 52%-48%.<ref name=\\\"politicoresults\\\">[http://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/house/florida/  2016 Florida House Election Results]</ref>\\n\\n==Early life and education==\\nCrist was born in [[Altoona, Pennsylvania]]<ref name=\\\"race\\\">{{cite news |url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sptimes/835232441.html?MAC=939a2bba9802553477e6bde045fe21f6&did=835232441&FMT=FT&FMTS=FT&date=May+9%2C+2005&author=LUCY+MORGAN&pub=St.+Petersburg+Times&printformat=&desc=Crist+will+enter+governor%27s+race  |title=Crist Will Enter Governor's Race  |last=Morgan  |first=Lucy  |accessdate=2007-01-12  |date=2005-05-09  |publisher=St. Petersburg Times  |pages=1A}}</ref> on July 24, 1956, to Charles Joseph Crist, Sr., an American physician of [[Greek Cypriot]] and [[Lebanese American|Lebanese]] descent,<ref name=\\\"billmaher\\\">{{cite episode |title=Charlie Crist, Tom Colicchio, Alicia Menendez, S. E. Cupp, P. J. O'Rourke| number=306 |episodelink=List of Real Time with Bill Maher episodes (2014)|series=[[Real Time with Bill Maher]] |network=HBO |airdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> and Nancy (n\\u00e9e Lee), of [[Scots-Irish American|Scots-Irish]], [[Swiss American|Swiss]], and [[Welsh American|Welsh]] descent.<ref name=\\\"billmaher\\\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2006/10/20/news_pf/State/Father_is_first_for_u.shtml |publisher=St. Petersburg Times |author=Steve Bousquet |title=Father is first for unmarried politico |date=October 20, 2006 }}</ref> His family name is adapted from the original Greek name \\\"[[Christodoulou]]\\\".<ref name=medved>{{cite web |url=http://townhall.com/Columnists/MichaelMedved/2008/05/28/the_gop_veep_list_pros_and_cons |title=The GOP Veep List: Pros and Cons |last=Medved |first=Michael |authorlink=Michael Medved |publisher=Townhall.com |date=28 May 2008 |accessdate=2008-10-15}}</ref>\\n\\nCrist moved to [[St. Petersburg, Florida]], as a child, where he attended Riviera Middle School, and [[Shorecrest Preparatory School]]<ref name=\\\"fcats\\\">{{cite news |title=PUBLIC EDUCATION: Like herding FCATs, Crist's challenge is elusive: Make accountability appealing. |publisher=St. Petersburg Times |date=February 25, 2007 |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2007/02/25/Opinion/Public_education__for.shtml }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Crist's politics getting greener; Not all support focus on global warming |publisher=''[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]'' (Florida) |date=April 22, 2007 |url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070422/NEWS/704220340 }}</ref> and graduated from [[St. Petersburg High School]] in 1974. He is the second of four children and has three sisters: Margaret Crist Wood, Elizabeth Crist Hyden, and Catherine Crist Kennedy. He attended [[Wake Forest University]] for two years, where he played quarterback for the [[Wake Forest Demon Deacons football]] team. Crist earned his undergraduate degree from [[Florida State University]] where he was elected Vice President of the student body and became a member of the [[Pi Kappa Alpha]] fraternity. He received his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] from [[Samford University]] [[Cumberland School of Law]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Charlie Crist: A fuzzy line divides personal and political lives |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2006/08/27/State/Charlie_Crist__A_fuzz.shtml |publisher=Sarasota Herald Tribute |date=August 27, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/politics/article/0,8599,1898151,00.html |publisher=Time Magazine |date=May 14, 2009 |author=Laura Fitzpatrick AND Lauren E. Bohn |title=2 Minute Bio}}</ref>\\n\\n==Early career==\\n\\n===Practicing law===\\nAfter graduating from the [[Cumberland School of Law]] in 1981, and having passed the bar on his third attempt,<ref>{{cite news |first=Stephen |last=Hegarty |title=Candidate failed 2 bar exams;Florida's top educator, who hopes to be its top legal officer, says failing taught him \\\"never give up.'' |url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/090101/State/Candidate_failed_2_ba.shtml |publisher=St. Petersburg Times |date=September 1, 2001 |accessdate=2008-05-25 }}</ref> Crist was hired as general counsel to [[Minor League Baseball]], which was headquartered in St. Petersburg. Drawn to politics, Crist was a candidate for public office for the first time in 1986, as a Republican, in the primary race for a state Senate seat in [[Pinellas County]]. After losing in a [[runoff election|runoff]], Crist joined his brother-in-law in private practice in St. Petersburg, but soon returned to politics as an aide in the successful 1988 United States Senate campaign of [[Connie Mack III]], whom he has since described as his political mentor.<ref name=\\\"guns\\\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tbo.com/news/metro/MGB5Q9E6NQE.html |date=August 9, 2006 |publisher=TBO.com News / The Tampa Tribune |author=William March |title=Sticking To His Guns |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060916182231/http://www.tbo.com/news/metro/MGB5Q9E6NQE.html |archivedate=September 16, 2006 }}</ref>\\n\\n===Florida Senate===\\nCrist was elected to a two-year term to the [[Florida Senate]] in 1992 from the 20th District, which encompassed parts of St. Petersburg and [[South Tampa]].<ref name=\\\"handbook\\\">{{cite book |title=''The Florida Handbook 2007\\u20132008'' |author1=Morris, Allen |author2=Joan Perry Morris, compilers |page=31 |edition=31st Biennial  |url=http://www.PeninsularPublishing.com |publisher=Peninsula Publishing |isbn=978-0-9765846-2-9}}</ref> Crist defeated longtime incumbent Democratic State Senator [[Helen Gordon Davis]] of [[Tampa]], 58.3 to 41.7%.<ref name=mh>{{cite news |first=Alex|last=Leary|title=Florida Democrats divided on redistricting, black representation |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2011/05/15/v-fullstory/2218391/florida-democrats-divided-on-redistricting.html |work=[[St. Petersburg Times]] |publisher=[[Miami Herald]]|date=2011-05-15 |accessdate=2011-05-16}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://results.elections.myflorida.com/Index.asp?ElectionDate=11/3/1992&DATAMODE=|title=November 3, 1992 General Election Official Results|date=|website=Florida Division of Elections Results Archive|publisher=Florida Department of State|access-date=June 17, 2016}}</ref> Crist was able to unseat Gordon Davis following the 1992 decennial [[redistricting]] process, which significantly reconfigured the districts in the Tampa Bay area.<ref name=mh/> His victory was credited with helping to end the 128-year control of the Florida Senate by the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], as the Republicans netted three Senate seats in 1992, resulting in a 20-20 tie between the two parties.<ref name=mh/>\\n\\nHe was known as a [[Law and order (politics)|law-and-order]] senator, sponsoring legislation requiring inmates to [[Truth in sentencing|serve at least 85% of their sentences]] before becoming eligible for parole.<ref name=\\\"race\\\" /> He supported teacher salary increases, [[charter school]]s, and a [[Vehicle registration plates of Florida|specialty license plate]] for [[Restoration of the Everglades|Everglades conservation]].<ref name=\\\"handbook\\\" /> With Crist as chairman, the Senate Ethics and Elections Committee investigated actions of then-governor [[Lawton Chiles]] amid allegations that Chiles' campaign had made [[push polling|\\\"scare calls\\\"]] to senior citizens days before the 1994 gubernatorial election. Chiles testified before the committee and admitted that his campaign had made the calls.<ref name=\\\"race\\\" /><ref name=\\\"guns\\\" />\\n\\nCrist was reelected to the Senate in 1994 to a four-year term, defeating Democrat Dana Lynn Maley with 63.3% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://results.elections.myflorida.com/Index.asp?ElectionDate=11/8/1994&DATAMODE=|title=November 8, 1994 General Election Official Results|website=Florida Division of Elections Results Archive|publisher=Florida Department of State|access-date=June 17, 2016}}</ref>\\n\\n===Florida Education Commissioner===\\nCrist gained recognition in 1998 as the Republican challenger to the incumbent Democratic U.S. Senator [[Bob Graham]]. He lost to Graham by 26 percentage points.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fec.gov/pubrec/fe1998/98senate.htm |title=1998 U.S. Senate results |publisher=[[Federal Elections Commission]] |accessdate=2008-11-13}}</ref>  He was elected [[Education Commissioner of Florida]] in 2000 \\u2013 a position he held until it became an appointed office 2003, due to a 1998 constitutional amendment.<ref name=\\\"guns\\\" />\\n\\nCrist left his position after he was elected Attorney General.\\n\\n==Political career==\\n\\n===Florida Attorney General===\\nIn 2002 Crist was elected as the Attorney General in Florida. He received support of his candidacy from the host of ''[[America's Most Wanted]]'', [[John Walsh (television host)|John Walsh]]. Walsh and other supporters of his work commented and cited his work with the [[Center for Missing and Exploited Children]].\\n\\nCrist was praised by civil rights and consumer groups for expanding the powers of the Attorney General, during his time in office. These powers enabled him and Attorneys General in the future to have greater powers when prosecuting in civil rights and fraud cases. He also worked at combatting [[E-mail spam|spam e-mail]] and froze utility rates. He focused on ending telecom deception and protecting the environment.<ref name=race /><ref name=\\\"smiles\\\">{{cite news |title=Victory Smiles at Charlie Crist  |publisher=The International Coordinating Committee \\\"Justice for Cyprus\\\" (PSEKA) |url=http://news.pseka.net/index.php?module=article&id=5900 |date=October 20, 2006}}</ref>\\n\\nIn 2004, Crist\\u2019s office began to investigate the [[Lou Pearlman]] case.  Jacqueline Dowd, who was leading the investigation, resigned and John MacGregor, who ended the investigation in 2004, replaced her.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/orlando/stories/2004/02/16/daily27.html |title=Dowd leaves attorney general's office |publisher=[[Orlando Business Journal]] |date=February 19, 2004 |last=Kreuger |first=Jill |accessdate=2008-10-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gainesville.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20061003/LOCAL/210030330/1078/news |publisher=[[The Gainesville Sun]] |title=Book: Crist tried to 'whitewash' probe |date=October 3, 2006 |last=Follick |first=Joe |accessdate=2008-10-15}}</ref> In 2006, [[Les Henderson]] criticized Crist\\u2019s handling of the Lou Pearlman scouting network and the investigation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2007/03/06/Business/Lawsuit_faults_Crist_.shtml |publisher=[[St. Petersburg Times]] |date=March 6, 2007 |title=Lawsuit faults Crist in giant Ponzi scheme |last=Huntley |first=Helen |accessdate=2008-10-15}}</ref>\\n\\nAs Attorney General, he disagreed with governor Jeb Bush in the [[Terri Schiavo case]]. Crist received criticism from both sides on this issue.<ref>[http://www.sptimes.com/2006/11/01/State/Schiavo_issue_haunts_.shtml Schiavo issue haunts Crist] Smith, Adam C. ''St. Petersburg Times''. November 1, 2006. Retrieved April 28, 2010.</ref>\\n\\n===Governor of Florida===\\n[[File:Charlie Crist cropped.jpg|thumb|Crist in Brazil, 2007.|250px]]\\n\\nCrist was inaugurated Governor of Florida on January 2, 2007. He was involved in changing policies including work on the purchase of a large area of sugar plantations. He also worked on education, with Florida rising into the top 10 for K12 education under his control.<ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Crist touts Florida's improvements in education rankings|url=http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2009/dec/21/charlie-crist/charlie-crist-touts-floridas-improvements-educatio/|publisher=Politifact|accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref>\\n\\n====Fiscal policies====\\nCrist supported President [[Barack Obama]]'s [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]], a stimulus package in response to the [[Great Recession]].<ref name=\\\"stimulus\\\">{{cite news|publisher=Forbes, Associated Press |title=Fla. gov touts stimulus package benefit at meeting |url=http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2009/01/27/ap5968997.html |date=January 27, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205123942/http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2009/01/27/ap5968997.html |archivedate=February 5, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Crist: Stimulus will help Florida |publisher=MSNBC |author=Morning Joe |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/3036789/#28933203}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |publisher=MSNBC Hardball |title=GOP Gov Support Obama Stimulus |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/21134540/vp/29001972#29001972 |date= }}</ref> Fellow Republicans were angered by Crist's support for the stimulus.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Miami Herald |title=GOP seethes over Charlie Crist's stimulus-plan support |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics/story/901859.html |author=Adam C. Smith |date=February 13, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091007103945/http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics/story/901859.html |archivedate=October 7, 2009 }}</ref>\\n\\nCrist called the act a \\\"godsend,\\\"<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/16/charlie-crist-effusive-ab_n_2146562.html Charlie Crist Effusive About Barack Obama at Tampa Press Banquet], ''Huffington Post'' (November 17, 2012).</ref> noting that it saved the jobs of nearly 20,000 Florida schoolteachers and other school workers in the 2009-10 period.<ref>Amy Sherman, [http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2012/sep/06/george-lemieux/charlie-crist-was-pro-life-pro-gun-and-anti-tax-sa/ Charlie Crist says in debate that stimulus saved 20,000 teacher jobs], PolitiFact Florida  (October 10, 2014).</ref>\\n\\n====Social policies====\\n\\n=====Capital punishment=====\\nAs governor, Crist supported [[capital punishment in Florida|capital punishment]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fadp.org/news/MH-20051103.htm |publisher=Miami Herald, via Herald.com |date=2 November 2005 |title=Crist: Hands off death penalty law |author=Lesley Clark |accessdate=August 20, 2009}}</ref>\\n\\n=====Gun rights=====\\nIn 2008 he signed a provision that prevents employers from prohibiting employees' bringing firearms to the workplace, as long as the weapons are secure and individuals maintain a concealed carry license.<ref>{{cite news|title=Crist signs bring your gun to work bill |publisher=Palm Beach Post |url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/politics/content/state/epaper/2008/04/15/0415gunsatwork.html |date=April 15, 2008 |author=Dara Kam |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080829174600/http://www.palmbeachpost.com/politics/content/state/epaper/2008/04/15/0415gunsatwork.html |archivedate=August 29, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Florida lawmakers pass \\\"take your guns to work\\\" law |publisher=Reuters |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSN0948339420080409 |date=April 9, 2008 }}</ref>\\n\\n=====Abortion=====\\nCrist's stance on abortion has been unclear at times.<ref name=CristHazy>Steve Bousquet, [http://www.sptimes.com/2006/08/18/State/Crist_s_stance_on_abo.shtml Crist's stance on abortion still hazy], ''St Petersburg Times'' (August 18, 2006).</ref> In 1995, while in Florida Senate, Crist joined with two Democrats in the Senate Health Care Committee in voting against a proposal for a mandatory 24-hour waiting period before a woman could have an abortion, resulting in a 3-3 tie vote and the defeat of the bill.<ref name=CristHazy/> In 1998, while running for the U.S. Senate, Crist wrote in a ''[[Tampa Bay Times]]'' questionnaire that \\\"I believe that a woman has the right to choose, but would prefer only after careful consideration and consultation with her family, her physician and her clergy; not her government.\\\"<ref name=CristHazy/> Crist said in a debate that year that he did not support a constitutional amendment banning abortion.<ref name=CristHazy/> In 2006, while running for governor, Crist said that he did not support overturning ''[[Roe v. Wade]]'' and opposed a mandatory 24-hour waiting period before a woman could have an abortion.<ref name=CristHazy/>\\n\\nIn 2010, while running for the U.S. Senate again, Crist said he would \\\"fight for pro-life legislative efforts\\\" and described himself as \\\"pro-life.\\\"<ref name=\\\"Politifact2012\\\">{{cite web|title=Charlie Crist was pro-life, pro-gun and anti-tax, says George LeMieux|url=http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2012/sep/06/george-lemieux/charlie-crist-was-pro-life-pro-gun-and-anti-tax-sa/|publisher=Politifact|accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref>  By March 2010, however, as rumors swirled that he would leave the Republican Party and become an independent, Crist reiterated that he did not support overturning ''Roe v. Wade'' and told a Christian Family Coalition group that \\\"We ought to instead of change laws, change hearts.\\\"<ref>Adam C. Smith, [http://www.tampabay.com/news/politics/stateroundup/amid-intense-chatter-crist-denies-he-would-run-as-independent/1076685 Amid intense chatter, Crist denies he would run as independent], ''St. Petersburg Times'' (March 2, 2010).</ref>\\n\\nIn June 2010, after leaving the Republican Party and becoming an independent, Crist removed anti-abortion language from his website.<ref name=\\\"WinterUltrasoundBill\\\">Michael Winter, [http://content.usatoday.com/communities/ondeadline/post/2010/06/florida-gov-charlie-crist-vetoes-ultrasound-abortion-bill/1?csp=34news Florida Gov. Charlie Crist vetoes ultrasound abortion bill] ''USA Today'' (June 11, 2010).</ref> Shortly thereafter, Crist vetoed a bill to require women seeking abortions to pay for an receive an [[ultrasound]], calling the measure \\\"punitive\\\" and \\\"almost mean-spirited.\\\"<ref name=\\\"Politifact2012\\\"/><ref name=\\\"WinterUltrasoundBill\\\"/> The bill also included language barring abortion coverage \\\"under a contract toward which any [[tax credit]] or cost-sharing credit is applied.\\\"<ref name=\\\"LarrabeeAbortionBill\\\">Brandon Larrabee, [http://jacksonville.com/news/florida/2010-06-01/story/abortion-bill-may-be-political-land-mine-crist Abortion bill may be political land mine for Crist], [[News Service of Florida]] (June 1, 2010).</ref> Legislative Republicans and [[anti-abortion movement|anti-abortion groups]] said that his language was aimed at preventing \\\"what they considered the possibility of federal funding being used for abortion in Florida,\\\"<ref name=\\\"WinterUltrasoundBill\\\"/><ref name=\\\"LarrabeeAbortionBill\\\"/> while [[abortion rights]] groups said that the broadly written provision would have resulted \\\"in hundreds of thousands of women losing health care coverage that they currently have.\\\"<ref name=\\\"LarrabeeAbortionBill\\\"/> The bill vetoed by Crist also included some provisions \\\"intended to thwart\\\" the [[Affordable Care Act]], the federal [[Health care reform in the United States|health care reform]] legislation championed by President Obama.<ref name=\\\"WinterUltrasoundBill\\\"/>\\n\\n=====Same-sex marriage and LGBT issues=====\\nIn 2006, as a proposed [[U.S. state constitutional amendments banning same-sex unions|state constitutional amendment banning same-sex unions]] was headed to the ballot in Florida, Crist said that such an amendment was unnecessary because state law already barred same-sex marriages.<ref name=\\\"MoorheadMarriage\\\">Molly Moorhead, [http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2013/may/09/charlie-crist/after-voting-ban-crist-now-backs-gay-marriage/ After voting for a ban, Charlie Crist now backs gay marriage], PolitiFact Florida (May 9, 2013).</ref> During the Republican primary, however, Crist went on to sign the petition for the amendment in September 2005 at the request of the [[Christian Coalition of America|Christian Coalition]].<ref name=\\\"MoorheadMarriage\\\"/><ref name=\\\"ShermanSSM\\\">Amy Sherman, [http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2014/feb/07/charlie-crist/he-changed-his-stance-gay-marriage-charlie-crist-s/ Before he changed his stance on gay marriage, Charlie Crist says he always supported civil unions] (February 7, 2014).</ref> Crist said in campaign materials at the time that he supported \\\"traditional marriage.\\\"<ref name=\\\"MoorheadMarriage\\\"/> In 2008, Crist said that he voted for the Florida amendment, which passed.<ref name=\\\"MoorheadMarriage\\\"/>\\n\\nIn a debate and a radio talk show appearance in 2006, Crist indicated support for [[civil union]]s.<ref name=\\\"ShermanSSM\\\"/> In 2010, after switching to become an independent during the U.S. Senate race, Crist declared his support for civil unions encompassing \\\"the full range of legal protections\\\" including \\\"access to a loved one in the hospital, inheritance rights, the fundamental things people need to take care of their families.\\\"<ref name=\\\"ShermanSSM\\\"/> It is unclear whether such civil unions would have been prohibited by the 2008 state constitutional amendment which Crist supported.<ref name=\\\"ShermanSSM\\\"/>\\n\\nAs governor, Crist deemphasized the marriage issue, saying in a CNN appearance in late 2007 that \\\"It's not an issue that moves me. I'm just a live and let live kind of guy\\\" and telling the ''Orlando Sentinel'' in 2008 that the issue was not \\\"top tier\\\" for him.<ref name=\\\"MoorheadMarriage\\\"/><ref name=\\\"ShermanSSM\\\"/>\\n\\nCrist initially supported Florida's ban on [[LGBT adoption|same-sex adoption]], which had been in place since 1977.<ref name=\\\"AdoptionSSM\\\">[http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2014/feb/20/charlie-crist/after-he-left-gop-charlie-crist-said-he-no-longer-/ On adoption by gay couples], PolitiFact (February 10, 2014).</ref>  Crist publicly expressed support for the ban from the time he was attorney general in 2006 to his early campaign for the U.S. Senate in 2010, even after some state legislators proposed dropping the ban in 2007 and a [[Miami-Dade County, Florida|Miami-Dade]] judge struck down the ban as unconstitutional in 2008.<ref name=\\\"AdoptionSSM\\\"/> Crist expressed support for the ban as late as February 2010.<ref name=\\\"AdoptionSSM\\\"/>\\n\\nBy June 2010, however, Crist expressed openness to changing Florida law to allow same-sex adoption, saying a better approach \\\"would be to let judges make that decision on a case-by-case basis.\\\"<ref name=\\\"AdoptionSSM\\\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/localgovernment/mccollum-touts-tax-freeze-crist-open-to-gay-adoption/1103181 |title=McCollum touts tax freeze; Crist open to gay adoption |last=Smith |first=Adam C. |date=June 18, 2010 |newspaper=St. Petersburg Times |publisher=tampabay.com |accessdate=September 9, 2010 |location=Sarasota, Florida}}</ref>\\n\\nIn September 2010, Crist said that he has had an \\\"appropriate evolution\\\" on gay rights and was considering dropping the state's appeal of the court ruling striking down Florida's ban on gay adoption.<ref name=\\\"LimAdoption\\\">Dara Kim, [http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2010-09-14/news/fl-crist-gay-rights-20100914_1_gay-adoption-gay-couples-charlie-crist Crist: I've had 'appropriate evolution' on gay rights], ''Palm Beach Post'' (September 14, 2010).</ref> Days later, after an appeals court struck down the ban, Crist hailed the ruling \\\"a very good day for Florida\\\" and \\\"a great day for children\\\" and announced that the state would no longer seek to enforce the ban.<ref name=\\\"AdoptionSSM\\\"/> In a Senate candidates' debate the next month, Crist attributed his shift in positions to \\\"the convergence of life experience and wisdom,\\\" saying that he had become more tolerant and become less judgmental with age.<ref name=\\\"AdoptionSSM\\\"/>\\n\\nIn January 2014, Crist apologized for his support for the 2008 same-sex marriage ban and for the same-sex adoption ban, telling an Orlando LGBT publication that \\\"I'm sorry I did that. It was a mistake. I was wrong. Please forgive me.\\\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Charlie Crist 'Sorry' He Backed Gay Marriage Ban, Calls It A 'Mistake'|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/02/charlie-crist-gay-marriage_n_4531810.html|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=15 January 2014|first=Luke|last=Johnson}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Crist apologizes for backing same-sex marriage ban|url=http://www.msnbc.com/the-last-word/crist-apologizes-lgbt-community|publisher=MSNBC|accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Crist Says 'Sorry' for Supporting Florida's Same-Sex Marriage Ban|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/politicians/2014/01/02/charlie-crist-says-sorry-supporting-floridas-marriage-ban|publisher=Advocate|accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>\\n\\n====Environmental work====\\n\\nAs an environmental advocate, Crist, in June 2008, proposed the State of Florida buy {{convert|187000|acre|km2}} from the United States Sugar Corporation for $1.2 billion. The purchase would remove about 187,000 acres of sugar farming for restoration efforts. In front of supporters in Palm Beach County, Crist described the deal \\\"as monumental as our nation's first national park.\\\"<ref>Guardian UK \\\"Florida to buy 187,000 farmland acres to preserve Everglades\\\" https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2008/jun/24/conservation.usa</ref>  Economic changes forced the purchase to be reduced to {{convert|73000|acre|km2}} of sugar and citrus plantations for Everglades restoration projects.<ref>Miami Herald \\\"Crist praises water managers for support of Big Sugar land buy\\\" [http://www.miamiherald.com/business/breaking-news/story/1048326.html]{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref><ref>Miami Herald \\\"Crist has competition: U.S. Sugar has offer from another suitor\\\" http://miamiherald.typepad.com/nakedpolitics/2008/11/crist-has-compe.html</ref><ref>AP \\\"Fla. revises deal with US Sugar to save Everglades\\\" By Jessica Gresko The Associated Press November 11, 2008 http://www.topix.com/content/ap/2008/11/fla-revises-deal-with-us-sugar-to-save-everglades</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Deal to Save Everglades May Help Sugar Firm|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/08/us/08everglades.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|publisher=NY Times|accessdate=29 January 2014|first1=Don|last1=Van Natta Jr|first2=Damien|last2=Cave|date=March 7, 2010}}</ref>\\n\\nHe announced plans to sign executive orders to impose strict [[air pollution]] standards in the state, with aims to reducing [[greenhouse gas]] emissions by 80 percent of the 1990 levels, by 2050 .<ref name=enn>{{cite news |publisher=Reuters |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/governmentFilingsNews/idUSN1125764520070711 |title=Florida To Introduce Tough Greenhouse Gas Targets |date=July 11, 2007 |author=Jim Loney |accessdate=August 21, 2009}}</ref> In his gubernatorial campaign, Crist opposed [[offshore oil drilling]]. Crist altered that position in June 2008, when oil reached peak prices, saying \\\"I mean, let's face it, the price of gas has gone through the roof, and Florida families are suffering, and my heart bleeds for them.\\\" <ref>\\\"Florida's Crist has new view of offshore drilling ban\\\" [http://www.breitbart.com/article.php?id=D91CGGV81&show_article=1] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110808070312/http://www.breitbart.com/article.php?id=D91CGGV81&show_article=1 |date=August 8, 2011 }}</ref><ref>\\\"In Switch, Florida's Crist Eyes Offshore Drilling\\\" NPR http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=91680890</ref>\\n\\n====Other work====\\n\\nCrist endorsed legislation requiring paper records of all ballots cast in an election, after claims that votes were undercounted in black communities by computerized voting machines. He supported  a large tax cut  which was to total $25 billion over a 5-year period. The tax cut was aimed at [[property tax]] relief.<ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Crist takes credit for Florida's largest ever tax cut|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2009/nov/10/charlie-crist/charlie-crist-is-taking-credit-for-floridas-larges/|publisher=Politifact|accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref>\\n\\nHe supported increased regulation of the insurance industry, including property insurance rates (in the aftermath of [[Hurricane Katrina]]) and health insurance. The [[Citizens Insurance#Florida|Citizen's Property Insurance Corp]] and the [http://www.sbafla.com/fhcf/ Florida Hurricane Catastrophe Fund] have been described as risky and underfunded. Standing next to former football star [[Dan Marino]] (whose son, Michael, is [[autism|autistic]] and who inspired the [[Dan Marino#Dan Marino Foundation|Dan Marino Foundation]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.childnett.tv/videos/stories/foundation_inspired_family |title=A Foundation Inspired by a Family |publisher=Childnett.Tv |accessdate=2010-08-17}}</ref>), Crist signed a law expanding health coverage statewide for autism disorders and he has also signed legislation expanding low-income coverage and creating public and private insurance options in the state.<ref>Insurance Journal \\\"Fla. Gov. Crist Persuades Cabinet to Block Insurers' Exit\\\" http://www.insurancejournal.com/news/southeast/2007/02/01/76468.htm</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flgov.com/release/9150 |title=Florida Governor Charlie Crist &#124; Governor Crist Launches \\\"Shop and Compare Insurance Rates\\\" Web Site |publisher=Flgov.com |accessdate=2010-08-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100514160300/http://www.flgov.com/release/9150 |archivedate=May 14, 2010 }}</ref><ref>\\\"Governor Crist Launches Shop and Compare Website\\\" http://www.ShopAndCompareRates.com and http://www.flgov.com</ref><ref>Wall Street Journal \\\"Florida's Unnatural Disaster Charlie Crist, taxpayers and the next hurricane.\\\" http://online.wsj.com/article/SB123371173559046209.html</ref><ref>Associated Press \\\"Crist: Florida 'better off' without State Farm\\\" http://www.gainesville.com/article/20090129/NEWS/901290919/0/LIVING</ref><ref>NPR \\\"State Farm Abandons Florida's Homeowners Market\\\" http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=99942808</ref>\\n\\n===Role in the 2008 presidential election===\\nSenator [[John McCain]]  endorsed Crist's 2006 campaign for Governor, traveling the state to campaign with him. The day before the general election, Crist held a campaign event with McCain in [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]]. Later, when the Republican Presidential primary debates were held in [[St. Petersburg, Florida|St. Petersburg]], Crist embraced McCain. Former [[New York City Mayor]] [[Rudy Giuliani]], who had also campaigned for Crist during the gubernatorial election, had sought his endorsement.<ref>Seattle Times \\\"We'll win Florida, Giuliani says\\\" http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/politics/2004121276_rudy12.html</ref><ref>MSNBC \\\"Giuliani pins his hopes on Florida\\\" http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/22706715/</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/politics/2008-01-30-104286216_x.htm |title=Gov Crist could benefit from McCain win |agency=Associated Press |last=Farrington |first=Brendan |date=January 30, 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-13 | work=USA Today}}</ref><ref>The Boston Globe \\\"Calling McCain a true American hero fla governor endorses\\\" [http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2008/01/27/calling_McCain_a_true_american_hero_fla_governor_endorses_senator/] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724120030/http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2008/01/27/calling_McCain_a_true_american_hero_fla_governor_endorses_senator/ |date=July 24, 2008 }}</ref>\\n\\nIn May 2007, Crist signed a bill moving the date of Florida's presidential primary to January 29, 2008, contrary to national political party rules.<ref>AP and Fox News \\\"Florida Governor Signs Bill to Move Up Presidential Primary to January\\\" [http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,274254,00.html] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070920173255/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,274254,00.html |date=September 20, 2007 }}</ref> Crist joined Michigan governor [[Jennifer Granholm]] in asking that their states' delegates be seated. Both national conventions ended up seating all delegates, but with only a half vote each for the sanctioned states.<ref>New York Times \\\"G.O.P. Plans Early-Primary Penalties\\\" http://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/29/us/politics/29calendar.html</ref><ref>Miami Herald \\\"All 114 FL delegates get seats on GOP convention floor\\\" http://miamiherald.typepad.com/nakedpolitics/2008/08/all-114-fl-dele.html</ref><ref>CNN \\\" Florida, Michigan get all delegates, but each gets half vote\\\" [http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/05/31/dems.delegates/index.html] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081113131005/http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/05/31/dems.delegates/index.html |date=November 13, 2008 }}</ref><ref>Politico \\\"Florida Gov. wants all delegates seated\\\" http://www.politico.com/blogs/thecrypt/0208/Florida_Gov_wants_all_delegates_seated.html</ref>\\n\\nOn January 26, 2008, He endorsed [[John McCain|McCain]] in the Republican primary race, saying, \\\"He's a great friend and will do a great job for the United States.\\\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/florida/story/395209.html |title=McCain scores Crist's endorsement |publisher=[[Miami Herald]] |date=January 26, 2008 |accessdate=2008-10-14}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> McCain later won the primary by five percentage points.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.flanews.com/?p=1693 |title=Crist\\u2019s Endorsement Helped McCain Defeat Romney |publisher=Capitol News Service |last=Ray |first=Whitney |date=January 27, 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-13}}</ref>\\n\\nOn October 28, 2008 Crist extended early voting hours of operation and declared that a \\\"state of emergency exists\\\" due to record voter turnout and resultant hours-long waits at locations throughout the state.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/the-trail/2008/10/28/crist_extends_early_voting_hou.html |title=Crist Extends Early Voting Hours in Fla. |publisher=The Washington Post |last=Flaherty |first=Mary Pat |date=October 28, 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics/florida/story/745715.html |title=Florida's Early Voting Hours Are Extended |publisher=[[The Miami Herald]] |last=Rabin |first=Charles |first2=Jennifer |last2=Lebovich |first3=Marc |last3=Caputo |date=October 29, 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-22}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\\n\\nOn October 29 and October 31, 2008, Crist appeared on [[MSNBC]]'s ''[[Morning Joe]]'' in which he told former Florida congressman [[Joe Scarborough]] that the race was tightening in Florida.<ref>{{cite video |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/21134540/vp/27470890#27470890 |publisher=[[MSNBC]]|people=Charlie Crist, Joe Scarborough |title=Morning Joe Interviews Crist on October 31, 2008 |date=October 28, 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|EvAgWmwPKHM|Morning Joe with Crist}}</ref>\\n\\n===2010 Senate campaign===\\n{{Main|United States Senate election in Florida, 2010}}\\n{{Wikinews|Musician David Byrne sues Florida governor over campaign song}}\\nCrist announced May 12, 2009 that he would not run for re-election as Governor in 2010, making him the first Florida governor not to run for reelection since 1964.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://editions.lib.umn.edu/smartpolitics/2013/04/02/charlie-crist-there-and-back-a/ |title= Charlie Crist: There and Back Again? |work=Smart Politics |first=Eric |last=Ostermeier |date= April 2, 2013}}</ref> Instead, he ran for the [[US Senate]], and his main Republican opponent was former Florida House Speaker [[Marco Rubio]],<ref>{{cite news |publisher=New York Times |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/13/us/13cristq.html |date=May 12, 2009 |title=Restless in Tallahassee, or With Eye on 2012, Governor Rolls Dice |author1=Damien Cave |author2=Gary Fineout |accessdate=August 21, 2009}}</ref><ref>Miami Herald \\\"Is Republican Party united behind Charlie Crist?\\\" [http://www.miamiherald.com/515/story/1045369.html]{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref> in addition to Democratic nominee [[Kendrick Meek]].<ref>{{cite news |publisher=Miami Herald |title=Kendrick Meek raises $1.5 million for Senate bid |author=Beth Reinhard |date=April 2, 2009|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/569/story/980067.html}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref>\\n\\nCrist was initially the front runner in the Republican primary, but later trailed Rubio in polls.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2010/04/15/politics/main6399577.shtml?tag=contentMain;contentBody|title=Poll: Crist Ahead If He Runs As Independent|date=April 15, 2010|work=CBS News|accessdate=17 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20002724-503544.html|title=Will Charlie Crist Run as an Independent?|last=Finn|first=Tyler|date=April 16, 2010|work=CBS News|accessdate=17 April 2010}}</ref>\\n\\nCrist announced his intent to run as an unaffiliated candidate in the 2010 senate election, while at the same time, according to a press release from his campaign, he remained a registered Republican.<ref name=\\\"OrlandoSentinel-Apr3010\\\">{{cite web| title = Crist\\u2019s independent run draws praise \\u2013 and scorn| url = http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2010-04-30/news/os-crist-independent-20100429_1_democratic-strategist-steve-schale-charlie-crist-independent-voters| accessdate =}}''Orlando Sentinel'', April 30, 2010.</ref> Crist officially changed his registration status to \\\"non party affiliated\\\" on May 13, 2010. Crist did not return campaign contributions made to him while a Republican.<ref>{{cite web|last=Reinhard |first=Beth |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2010/05/13/1626770/crist-no-refunds-for-former-fans.html |title=Charlie Crist won't refund campaign donations - Florida |publisher=MiamiHerald.com |date=2010-05-13 |accessdate=2010-08-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605140510/http://www.miamiherald.com/2010/05/13/1626770/crist-no-refunds-for-former-fans.html |archivedate=June 5, 2010 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2010/may/19/charlie-crist/gov-charlie-crist-changes-course-keeping-campaign-/ Gov. Charlie Crist changes course on returning campaign donations] Politifact  (Tampa Bay Tribune / Miami Herald) May 19, 2010 ''Crist said he would \\\"probably give it back to them,\\\" leading donors to believe that as the dictionary states it was \\\"to be expected\\\" or \\\"without much doubt\\\" that they would see some of their cash back from Crist. We find Crist completely changed his position from entertaining the idea of giving the money back, to definitely not giving the money back. Our verdict: Full Flop.''</ref> Crist withdrew from the Republican primary after trailing Marco Rubio in pre-primary polling, and then lost the general election, receiving 29.7% of the vote, compared to 48.9% for Rubio and 20.2% for the Democratic Party candidate Meek.<ref>{{cite web|last=Florida Division of Elections |url=https://election.dos.state.fl.us/elections/resultsarchive/Index.asp?ElectionDate=11/2/2010&DATAMODE= |title=Official Results of 2010 Election}}</ref>\\n\\nIn April 2011, as part of a settlement of a copyright lawsuit brought by musician [[David Byrne]], Crist apologized for his Senate campaign's use of Byrne's song \\\"[[Road to Nowhere]]\\\" without permission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.yahoo.com/blogs/ticket/david-byrne-forces-charlie-crist-record-embarrassing-apology-20110412-103915-351.html|title=David Byrne forces Charlie Crist to record embarrassing apology for stealing Talking Heads song}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s4k13LmlcUE|title=Charlie Crist Official Apology to David Byrne for Copyright Infringement}}</ref>\\n\\nBy the spring of 2015 there was media speculation Crist would seek the Democratic nomination for Florida's 2016 senate race.  This would mark his third run for the senate seat (he lost in 1998 and 2010).  However, in March 2015 Crist stated he would not seek the nomination.  That same month he endorsed U.S. Congressman Patrick Murphy's candidacy for the senate race.\\n\\n===Post-gubernatorial career===\\nIn January 2011, Crist joined personal injury law firm [[Morgan & Morgan PA|Morgan & Morgan]] in [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]].<ref name=\\\"DixonMorgan\\\">Matt Dixon, [http://www.naplesnews.com/news/state/charlie-crist-touted-as-attorney-for-morgan--morgan-but-hasnt-been-in-court-ep-504428072-341006661.html Charlie Crist: Touted as attorney for Morgan & Morgan, but hasn't been in court], ''Naples Daily News'' (July 21, 2014).</ref> Crist serves as a \\\"[[Rainmaker (business)|rainmaker]]\\\" for the firm and does not regularly appear in court.<ref name=\\\"DixonMorgan\\\"/>\\n\\nIn 2013, Crist performed paid consulting work for Coastal Construction, a Miami-based construction firm owned by Crist's longtime friend Tom Murphy, who is the father of U.S. Representative [[Patrick Murphy (Florida politician)|Patrick Murphy]].<ref name=\\\"DixonMorgan\\\"/>\\n\\nCrist has been a part-time guest lecturer at [[Stetson University College of Law]],<ref>Becky Bowers, [http://www.tampabay.com/news/politics/gubernatorial/charlie-crist-is-a-big-hit-in-first-law-lecture-at-stetson/1163329 Charlie Crist is a big hit in first law lecture at Stetson], ''Tampa Bay Times'' (April 12, 2011).</ref>  with the title of Distinguished Professorial Lecturer.<ref>[http://www.stetson.edu/law/news/index.php/2011/02/28/crist-will-be-distinguished-professorial-lecturer/ Crist will be Distinguished Professorial Lecturer], Stetson University (February 28, 2011).</ref>\\n\\nIn August 2012, Crist endorsed President [[Barack Obama]] in his [[Barack Obama presidential campaign, 2012|campaign for re-election]] over Republican nominee [[Mitt Romney]], saying that the Republican Party \\\"pitched so far to the extreme right on issues important to women, immigrants, seniors and students that they've proven incapable of governing for the people.\\\"<ref>Vanessa Williams, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/election-2012/wp/2012/08/26/former-fla-governor-charlie-crist-endorses-obama/ Former Fla. governor Charlie Crist endorses Obama], ''Washington Post'' (August 26, 2012).</ref><ref>Charlie Crist, [Here's why I'm backing Barack Obama], ''Tampa Bay Times'' (August 26, 2012).</ref> Crist was a speaker at the [[2012 Democratic National Convention]] in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]], saying \\\"I didn't leave the Republican Party; it left me.\\\"<ref>Emily Schultheis, [http://www.politico.com/story/2012/09/crist-speaks-to-dem-convention-080883 Charlie Crist defends Obama at DNC], ''Politico'' (September 6, 2012).</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hwYVraqaTn4 Charlie Crist Remarks at 2012 Democratic National Convention] (official video).</ref>\\n\\nOn December 7, 2012, Crist announced via [[Twitter]] that he had joined the Democratic Party.<ref name=\\\"changing\\\"/>\\n\\n===2014 gubernatorial election===\\n{{Main|Florida gubernatorial election, 2014}}\\nIn July 2013, it was announced that Crist would be releasing a new book and it was in the process of being written.<ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Crist has \\\"no-holds-barred\\\" book coming out|url=http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/the-buzz-florida-politics/charlie-crist-has-no-holds-barred-book-coming-out/2130689|publisher=Tampa Bay|accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Charlie Crist Is Writing A Book Because He Is Likely Going To Run For Governor Of Florida|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/10/charlie-crist-book-florida_n_3575416.html|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=15 January 2014|first=Jason|last=Linkins|date=July 10, 2013}}</ref> The release hinted he would be running in the 2014 gubernatorial election. The book, released in February 2014, is titled ''The Party's Over: How the Extreme Right Hijacked the GOP and I Became a Democrat''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Florida Governor Charlie Crist attacks rivals in new book|url=http://www.wtsp.com/rss/article/351855/250/Charlie-Crist-attacks-rivals-in-new-book|publisher=WTSP|accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Crist attacks rivals in new book|url=http://jacksonville.com/opinion/blog/403455/matt-dixon/2014-01-08/charlie-crist-attacks-rivals-book|publisher=Jacksonville|accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>  The book details why Crist became a Democrat and left the Republican Party.<ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Crist's new book: Rick Scott is a 'terrible governor,' Sarah Palin is 'different'|url=http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/the-buzz-florida-politics/charlie-crists-new-book-rick-scott-is-a-terrible-governor-sarach-palin-is/2160188|publisher=Tampa Bay|accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref> On November 1, 2013, Crist filed to run for governor as a Democrat.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ex-GOP Fla. Gov. Crist to run for job as Democrat|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/nov/1/ex-gop-fla-gov-crist-run-job-democrat/|publisher=Washington Times|accessdate=1 November 2013}}</ref>\\n\\nHaving won the Democratic nomination, Crist was defeated in the 2014 gubernatorial election by Republican  incumbent [[Rick Scott]].\\n\\nCrist holds the rare distinction of losing a statewide general election in Florida as a Republican, Democrat and Independent candidate.\\n\\n===2016 Congressional campaign===\\nOn October 20, 2015, Crist announced that he would seek the Democratic nomination for [[Florida's 13th congressional district]], his home district, in the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2016|2016 U.S. House of Representatives elections]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Join the discussion: Click to view comments, add yours |url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/politics/stateroundup/charlie-crist-announces-hes-running-for-congress/2250475 |title=Former Florida Gov. Charlie Crist announces he's running for Congress &#124; Tampa Bay Times |publisher=Tampabay.com |date= |accessdate=2015-10-21}}</ref> He had previously announced on [[Twitter]] that he would not run for [[political office]] in [[United States elections, 2016|2016]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/CharlieCrist/status/577582802796875776 |title=Charlie Crist on Twitter: \\\"I will not be seeking office in 2016, but I will be working alongside my fellow @FlaDems. Join me at http://t.co/VGsDGXVgvk.\\\" |publisher=Twitter.com |date=2015-03-16 |accessdate=2015-10-21}}</ref>  Republican incumbent [[David Jolly]], who succeeded 43-year incumbent [[Bill Young]] in a 2014 special election,  was vacating the seat to run for the same Senate seat for which Crist ran in 1998.  \\n\\nHowever, when Senator [[Marco Rubio]] decided to run for re-election, Jolly decided to drop out of the Senate race and seek re-election to the House.  He did so even though the 13th had been made significantly bluer when a court tossed out Florida's original congressional map. The new map drew nearly all of St. Petersburg, along with most of the more Democratic southern portion of Pinellas County, into the 13th.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wusfnews.wusf.usf.edu/post/crist-revives-political-career-win-over-jolly|title=Crist Revives Political Career With Win over Jolly|publisher=[[WUSF-FM]]|author1=Steve Newborn|author2=Mark Schreiner|date=2016-11-09}}</ref> Crist defeated Jolly,<ref name=\\\"politicoresults\\\"/> becoming the first Democrat to win this seat since 1955.\\n\\n==Political positions==\\n\\n===Future of the Republican Party===\\nOn November 12\\u201314, 2008, Crist hosted the [[Republican Governors Association]] (RGA) annual meeting in [[Miami, FL|Miami]]. Held the week after the [[United States elections, 2008|Democratic Party victories in the 2008 election]],<ref>CBS News \\\"Barack Obama Wins Presidency\\\" http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/11/04/politics/main4571289.shtml</ref> there was speculation about the tone of the Republican Governors meeting. Then Alaska governor [[Sarah Palin]], the defeated 2008 Republican vice presidential nominee, was a featured participant and speaker.\\n\\nCrist's speech at the RGA conference, \\\"Listen to the Voters and Serve\\\" included his sentiments on how the GOP should evolve: {{quote|This party can no longer hope to reach Hispanics, African Americans and other minority groups&nbsp;\\u2013 we need to just do it. Embracing cultures and lifestyles will make us a better party and better leaders. This desire for inclusiveness is near and dear to my heart... Last week, the American people made a choice and this week, if we choose to call ourselves leaders, if we truly endeavor to serve with a servant's heart for the people who count on us, then we too must work together, listen to one another and learn from the leaders who made the kind of history the American people deserve.<ref>A Message from Charlie \\\"Listen to the Voters and Serve\\\" By Charlie Crist http://www.charliecrist.com/</ref>}}\\n\\nCrist held a joint interview with Governor [[Mark Sanford]] of [[South Carolina]] and they discussed the split in the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] over where to direct the party's next efforts to gain more voters.<ref>Bloomberg News \\\"Governors Crist, Sanford Split Over Republican Path to Success\\\" http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=aahiSQ2bhTN8&refer=us</ref>\\n\\n===Same-sex marriage===\\nOn May 9, 2013, Crist announced that he supports [[Same-sex marriage in the United States|same-sex marriage]]; \\u201cI most certainly support marriage equality in Florida and look forward to the day it happens here.\\u201d<ref name=\\\"WP Gay Marriage\\\">{{cite news|last=Weiner|first=Rachel|title=Charlie Crist endorses gay marriage|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2013/05/09/charlie-crist-endorses-gay-marriage/|accessdate=22 May 2013|newspaper=Washington Post|date=May 9, 2013|quote=\\u201cI most certainly support marriage equality in Florida and look forward to the day it happens here,\\u201d the Republican-turned-independent-turned-Democrat wrote on his Facebook page. He congratulated Delaware on becoming the 11th state to legalize gay marriage.}}</ref> In both 2006 and 2008, Crist announced his support for the [[Federal Marriage Amendment]] although by 2010, he had endorsed adoption rights for gay couples.<ref name=\\\"WP Gay Marriage\\\" /><ref name=WG>{{cite news|last=Associated Press release|title=Ex-Republican Charlie Crist backs gay marriage|url=http://www.wisconsingazette.com/national-gaze/ex-republican-charlie-crist-backs-gay-marriage.html|accessdate=22 May 2013|newspaper=Wisconsin Gazette|date=May 9, 2013|quote=The statement marks a shift in Crist's views on gay marriage. He once supported Florida's constitutional ban on gay marriage, but also later said he wouldn't support a similar federal ban.}}</ref>\\n\\n===United States embargo against Cuba===\\nCrist wants to lift the [[United States embargo against Cuba]], saying it has not helped to change the government of [[Cuba]]. He had supported the embargo earlier as Republican and independent.<ref>[http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/article1960168.html Charlie Crist flip-flops on U.S. embargo against Cuba]</ref>\\n\\n==Personal life==\\n[[File:MMCrist.JPG|thumb|right|170px|Charlie Crist with his wife [[Carole Crist]]]]\\nIn July 1979, Crist married Amanda Morrow. They divorced within a year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2006/08/27/State/Charlie_Crist__A_fuzz.shtml |title=Charlie Crist: A fuzzy line divides personal and political lives |publisher=[[St. Petersburg Times]] |date=August 27, 2006 |last=Bousquet |first=Steve |accessdate=2008-10-12}}</ref>\\n\\nCrist became engaged to [[Carole Rome]] on July 3, 2008 after 9 months of dating, and was married<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.tampabay.com/buzz/2008/12/arrivals-to-cri.html |title=Crist\\u2013Rome Wedding Photos |publisher=[[St. Petersburg Times]] |date=December 12, 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-13}}</ref> on December 12 of that year at the [[First Methodist Church of St. Petersburg]], where Crist is a member.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cbs4.com/local/Florida.Governor.Charlie.2.790985.html |title=Governor Crist and Carole Rome set wedding date |publisher=[[WFOR-TV]] |accessdate=2008-10-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007023354/http://cbs4.com/local/Florida.Governor.Charlie.2.790985.html |archivedate=October 7, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dolinski|first=Catherine|title=Crist's December Wedding Will Follow Tradition|date=2008-11-13|publisher=''[[The Tampa Tribune]]''|page=6}}</ref>\\n\\n{{clear}}\\n\\n==Books==\\n\\n* ''The Party's Over: How the Extreme Right Hijacked the GOP and I Became a Democrat'' (2014) ISBN 978-0525954415\\n\\n==References==\\n{{Reflist|30em}}\\n\\n==External links==\\n{{Portal|Florida}}{{Wikinews|Musician David Byrne sues Florida governor over campaign song}}\\n* [http://www.charliecrist.com/ Charlie Crist] ''official campaign site''\\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Florida/Society_and_Culture/Politics/Candidates_and_Campaigns/Governor/Charlie_Crist}}\\n* {{CongLinks | congbio = | votesmart = | washpo = | govtrack = | cspan = | ontheissuespath = | surge = | legistorm = | fec = S6FL00160 | opensecrets = | followthemoney = | nyt = c/charlie_crist | findagrave = }}\\n\\n{{s-start}}\\n{{s-ppo}}\\n{{s-bef|before=[[James W. Grant|Bill Grant]]}}\\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[United States Senator|U.S. Senator]] from [[Florida]]<br>([[Classes of United States Senators|Class 3]])|years=[[United States Senate election in Florida, 1998|1998]]}}\\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mel Martinez]]}}\\n|-\\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Bludworth]]}}\\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[Florida Attorney General|Attorney General of Florida]]|years=[[Florida Attorney General election, 2002|2002]]}}\\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bill McCollum]]}}\\n|-\\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeb Bush]]}}\\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[List of Governors of Florida|Governor of Florida]]|years=[[Florida gubernatorial election, 2006|2006]]}}\\n{{s-aft|after=[[Rick Scott]]}}\\n|-\\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alex Sink]]}}\\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[List of Governors of Florida|Governor of Florida]]|years=[[Florida gubernatorial election, 2014|2014]]}}\\n{{s-inc|recent}}\\n|-\\n{{s-off}}\\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tom Gallagher]]}}\\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Florida Department of Education|Education Commissioner of Florida]]|years=2001\\u20132003}}\\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Horne (politician)|Jim Horne]]}}\\n|-\\n{{s-bef|before=Jeb Bush}}\\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Governors of Florida|Governor of Florida]]|years=2007\\u20132011}}\\n{{s-aft|after=Rick Scott}}\\n|-\\n{{s-legal}}\\n{{s-bef|before=[[Richard E. Doran|Richard Doran]]}}\\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Florida Attorney General|Attorney General of Florida]]|years=2003\\u20132007}}\\n{{s-aft|after=Bill McCollum}}\\n|-\\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Jolly]]}}\\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Florida|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Florida's 13th congressional district]]<br>{{small|Elect}}|years=Takin